6. Machine Learning Model

A Linear Regression algorithm was selected for this project because the target variable (Sales) is continuous.

The dataset was divided into:

Training Data: 80%
Testing Data: 20%

The model was trained using the training dataset and evaluated on the testing dataset.

7. Model Performance

The trained model was evaluated using three commonly used regression metrics.

Mean Absolute Error (MAE)

1.46

This indicates that, on average, the predicted sales differ from the actual sales by approximately 1.46 units.

Mean Squared Error (MSE)

3.17

The MSE measures the average squared prediction error. A lower value indicates better prediction accuracy.

R² Score

0.8994 (89.94%)

The model explains approximately 89.94% of the variation in product sales, indicating excellent predictive performance.

8. Key Findings

The following observations were made from the analysis:

TV advertising has the strongest impact on product sales.
Radio advertising also contributes positively to sales.
Newspaper advertising has the weakest influence on sales.
The dataset contains no missing or duplicate values.
The Linear Regression model achieved high prediction accuracy with an R² score of 89.94%.
9. Conclusion

This project successfully demonstrates how Machine Learning can be used for sales prediction. The dataset was cleaned, analyzed, and visualized before training a Linear Regression model. The model achieved an R² Score of 89.94%, indicating excellent predictive capability.

Sales prediction helps businesses optimize advertising budgets, improve marketing strategies, and make informed business decisions.

